carcnew<-carc[,-c(3,4,13)]
distance<-dist(carcnew)
hc1<-hclust(distance)
plot(hc1,xlab = "Observations", ylab = "Proximity measure")

it shows that maybe 5 is a reasonable number of cluster.

application of the hierarchical clustering method with 5 clusters.

cuthc1 = cutree(hc1,5)
labelColors = c("red", "green", "blue","violet","orange")
colLab<- function(n){if (is.leaf(n)){a<-attributes(n)
labCol<-labelColors[cuthc1[which(names(cuthc1) == a$label)]]
attr(n,"nodePar")<-c(a$nodePar, lab.col = labCol)}
  n}
clusDendro = dendrapply(as.dendrogram(hc1), colLab)
plot(clusDendro, main = "", type = "triangle")

### k-means,I tried 5, but it seems not good,3 is better.

K5means<- kmeans(carcnew, centers= 5)
colVector <- as.numeric(K5means$cluster)
plot(carcnew$P ~ carcnew$G, bg = colVector, xlab="",ylab = "", pch=21 ,col="black")
points(K5means$centers[,1] ~ K5means$centers[,5], col ="black", pch = 8, cex = 2)
text(carcnew, lables=rownames(carcnew), col=colVector, cex = 0.5)
## Warning in text.default(carcnew, lables = rownames(carcnew), col = colVector, :
## "lables" is not a graphical parameter

Kmeans<- kmeans(carcnew, centers= 3)
colVector <- as.numeric(Kmeans$cluster)
plot(carcnew$P ~ carcnew$G, bg = colVector, xlab="",ylab = "", pch=21 ,col="black")
points(Kmeans$centers[,1] ~ Kmeans$centers[,3], col ="black", pch = 8, cex = 2)
text(carcnew, lables=rownames(carcnew), col=colVector, cex = 0.5)
